I suspect you might be immune, because you have just made up your mind for whatever reason, but have some facts anyway...
All major brands have about 1% loss per year.
[https://energyinformative.org/lifespan-solar-panels/]

For monocrystalline silicon, the most commonly used panel for commercial and residential PV, the degradation rate is less than 0.5% for panels made before 2000, and less than 0.4% for panels made after 2000. That means that a panel manufactured today should produce 92% of its original power after 20 years, quite a bit higher than the 80% estimated by the 1% rule.
[https://www.engineering.com/DesignerEdge/DesignerEdgeArticles/ArticleID/7475/What-Is-the-Lifespan-of-a-Solar-Panel.aspx]

posts.body:
>>868b7efb-f5bf-4b90-bd25-7f1797cf838d
Longest Lasting: 30+ Years of Reliable Service

30+ Year Life Expectancy is actually an understatement for Nickel Iron batteries. Because Nickel Iron batteries use Nickel plates and an alkaline electrolyte, they don’t experience the plate degradation and short life of a lead plate in acid. It is common to see 50+ year old Nickel Iron batteries still in service today, with some dating back to the 1940s! 

10 Year Warranty is standard on all Iron Edison Nickel Iron Batteries.
[https://ironedison.com/nickel-iron-ni-fe-battery]

And Tesla Powerwall 2 ?
"If made into a car battery pack, 1,200 cycles would translate to roughly 300,000 miles (480,000 km) – meaning that a battery pack could still retain about 95% of its original energy capacity after ~300,000 miles – or 25 years at the average 12,000 miles per year."

... and there are a LOT of companies further developing and refining what is used in products today, and also a bunch of new and exciting stuff like "XNRGI has developed a lithium metal battery utilizing porous silicon as the electrode substrate and by merging the battery design with the low cost and manufacturing benefits of the silicon industry."
